of Woodstock, the Black Prince. Despite these transgressions, she later became one of the most influential people in the realm and a highly respected source of stability. Her life provides a distinctive perspective of a noblewoman at the heart of affairs in fourteenth-century England, a period when the Crown, despite enjoying some striking triumphs, also faced a series of political and social crises which shook conventional expectations. Furthermore, her life adds depth to our understanding of a time when marriage began to be regarded not just as a dynastic arrangement but a contract freely entered into by a couple. This accessibly written account of her life sets her in the full context of her world, and vividlyportrays a spirited medieval woman who was determined to be mistress of her fate and to make a mark in challenging times. The late Anthony Goodman was Professor Emeritus of Medieval and Renaissance History at the University of Edinburgh. His numerous publications include John of Gaunt; The Wars of the Roses; and Margery Kempe and Her World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrincesseszEnglandvBiography. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBiography.  aBlack Prince.  aEdward of Woodstock.  aFeminism.  aFourteenth-century England.  aGender history.  aGender politics.  aJoan Plantagenet.  aKent.  aMedieval female.  aMedieval marriage.  aMedieval royalty.  aMedieval.  aMiddle Age.  aRichard II.  aWomen's studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204953140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782049531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782049531/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017